00:26:39,793 --> 00:26:41,614
Two minutes, two questions I guess.

536
00:26:43,435 --> 00:26:47,256
Hello, so have you run into any problems

537
00:26:47,316 --> 00:26:49,717
with the completionists?

538
00:26:50,257 --> 00:26:56,780
Because in this web of possible actions in your quests,

539
00:26:57,240 --> 00:26:57,820
there's always...

540
00:26:58,801 --> 00:27:01,425
one way to get the most benefit of.

541
00:27:01,525 --> 00:27:03,328
And people sometimes will feel like

542
00:27:03,788 --> 00:27:05,852
I'm not playing the game 100%

543
00:27:06,413 --> 00:27:08,836
if I don't go through all the possible steps

544
00:27:08,896 --> 00:27:11,240
I can do certain quests.

545
00:27:11,540 --> 00:27:12,322
Do you have any?

546
00:27:12,402 --> 00:27:14,044
Well, the idea was to actually not...

547
00:27:14,525 --> 00:27:20,010
make it not even possible to play the quest in all possible ways in one single sitting.

548
00:27:20,410 --> 00:27:28,257
But for completion's sake, there were key points in every quest, like one of endings or something

549
00:27:28,277 --> 00:27:34,082
like that, and these counted to the completion ratio of the whole game. So although we did

550
00:27:34,122 --> 00:27:38,225
have non-linearity, we also had these choke points sometimes for these specific purposes.

551
00:27:43,219 --> 00:27:43,959
Yeah, another question?

552
00:27:44,359 --> 00:27:46,900
Yeah, just something quite interesting that you mentioned.

553
00:27:46,920 --> 00:27:49,240
You mentioned a single player action,

554
00:27:49,260 --> 00:27:54,142
you know, causing and having a causal reaction

555
00:27:54,242 --> 00:27:55,802
on multiple threads in a way.

556
00:27:55,822 --> 00:28:00,723
And in this complex graph, how much interplay is there

557
00:28:00,823 --> 00:28:02,863
between the different threads in your graph

558
00:28:03,103 --> 00:28:05,344
and how do you manage that complexity?

559
00:28:05,364 --> 00:28:08,585
Because that can easily exponentially, you know, explode.

560
00:28:09,279 --> 00:28:12,400
Okay, so the question was how do we manage actually

561
00:28:12,420 --> 00:28:14,000
the complexity that the graph,

562
00:28:14,641 --> 00:28:16,781
complexity grows exponentially with every node added.

563
00:28:16,921 --> 00:28:19,222
But specifically with the interplay of,

564
00:28:19,582 --> 00:28:22,723
if there is much interplay between the threads

565
00:28:23,643 --> 00:28:24,824
in the quests, if that makes sense.

566
00:28:24,864 --> 00:28:26,884
Yeah, essentially if I understand correctly,

567
00:28:26,924 --> 00:28:29,705
if there's interplay between certain parts of a quest,

568
00:28:29,905 --> 00:28:31,185
how do we manage the complexity of that?

569
00:28:31,545 --> 00:28:32,926
Well, we have very good tools.

570
00:28:34,753 --> 00:28:36,673
So essentially we create a specific editor

571
00:28:36,733 --> 00:28:41,554
that allows the designer to see the state of a quest exactly,

572
00:28:41,595 --> 00:28:43,315
which nodes are blocked, which are available,

573
00:28:43,335 --> 00:28:45,375
which are completed during play through of a quest.

574
00:28:45,715 --> 00:28:47,256
So by playing a couple of times

575
00:28:47,316 --> 00:28:50,837
and seeing how everything lights up and lights down,

576
00:28:51,197 --> 00:28:52,657
it's also possible to figure out

577
00:28:53,197 --> 00:28:55,658
what is not going okay, what's not right.

578
00:28:55,958 --> 00:28:58,778
Plus we had some debugging tools specific for these purposes.

579
00:28:59,258 --> 00:29:02,599
But in the end, nobody created such complicated quests

580
00:29:02,679 --> 00:29:04,900
that they were impossible to figure out what's wrong with them.

581
00:29:05,360 --> 00:29:07,941
Okay, but there wasn't that much interplay between quests?

582
00:29:08,581 --> 00:29:10,081
Between quests, not so much.

